is near to Veracruz along
the Gulf Coast of Mexico,

00:49:02.970 --> 00:49:06.950 align:middle line:84%
this giant basalt
head was completely

00:49:06.950 --> 00:49:13.080 align:middle line:84%
buried in the ground, as were
almost all of these huge heads.

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:14.850 align:middle line:90%
And people were walking over it.

00:49:14.850 --> 00:49:17.270 align:middle line:84%
And a trail happened
to just pass over

00:49:17.270 --> 00:49:22.780 align:middle line:84%
the forehead of this
giant buried head.

00:49:22.780 --> 00:49:25.310 align:middle line:84%
And eventually
archeologists realized

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:29.960 align:middle line:84%
that, yeah, this rock that
was just exposed on this trail

00:49:29.960 --> 00:49:37.130 align:middle line:84%
was part of this huge and
beautifully carved Olmec head.

00:49:37.130 --> 00:49:40.840 align:middle line:84%
And of course, like many
of the giant Olmec heads,

00:49:40.840 --> 00:49:44.370 align:middle line:90%
it looks very African.

00:49:44.370 --> 00:49:47.240 align:middle line:84%
When we look at
the heads, we see

00:49:47.240 --> 00:49:50.580 align:middle line:84%
that not only are they
colossal, weighing many tons,

00:49:50.580 --> 00:49:53.550 align:middle line:84%
but the facial
features seem to not

00:49:53.550 --> 00:49:57.780 align:middle line:84%
be American Indian
but more African,

00:49:57.780 --> 00:50:02.520 align:middle line:84%
with the wide nose,
and the thick lips.

00:50:02.520 --> 00:50:05.970 align:middle line:84%
They're wearing some
kind of leather helmet.

00:50:05.970 --> 00:50:09.910 align:middle line:84%
They have the stern
expressions of warriors.

00:50:09.910 --> 00:50:14.065 align:middle line:84%
Many Olmec statues have a
trademark frown on their face.

00:50:14.065 --> 00:50:16.570 align:middle line:90%


00:50:16.570 --> 00:50:20.460 align:middle line:84%
All of these features
puzzle archeologists.

00:50:20.460 --> 00:50:22.940 align:middle line:84%
And it's one of the
mysteries of the Olmecs.

00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:26.230 align:middle line:84%
They appear to be
Negroes from Africa.

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:29.040 align:middle line:84%
Many of them have thick
beards and mustaches

00:50:29.040 --> 00:50:33.340 align:middle line:84%
and appear to be Caucasians
from the eastern Mediterranean.

00:50:33.340 --> 00:50:38.810 align:middle line:84%
Other Olmecs seem very Oriental
and Chinese in their look.

00:50:38.810 --> 00:50:43.100 align:middle line:84%
Is it possible that thousands
of years ago in southern Mexico

00:50:43.100 --> 00:50:48.290 align:middle line:84%
and Guatemala and Honduras
that this area was

00:50:48.290 --> 00:50:53.960 align:middle line:84%
some kind of trading zone
where ships and seafarers came

00:50:53.960 --> 00:50:57.840 align:middle line:84%
across the Atlantic,
across the Pacific,

00:50:57.840 --> 00:51:00.070 align:middle line:90%
meeting in Central America.

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:04.690 align:middle line:84%
And this early culture is
known today as the Olmecs.

00:51:04.690 --> 00:51:07.470 align:middle line:84%
With some of these
colossal heads,

00:51:07.470 --> 00:51:11.840 align:middle line:84%
they are intricately
carved out of basalt,

00:51:11.840 --> 00:51:15.470 align:middle line:90%
which is extremely hard stone.

00:51:15.470 --> 00:51:21.240 align:middle line:84%
And carving these basalt heads,
in my mind, would have required

00:51:21.240 --> 00:51:26.740 align:middle line:84%
some pretty advanced technology
and tools, including, I think,

00:51:26.740 --> 00:51:27.960 align:middle line:90%
power tools.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:31.010 align:middle line:84%
In fact, one of
the colossal heads

00:51:31.010 --> 00:51:39.400 align:middle line:84%
from San Lorenzo was very
interesting and unique because

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:46.100 align:middle line:84%
it was a 20-ton basalt
head, but along parts

00:51:46.100 --> 00:51:50.880 align:middle line:84%
of the top of the helmet are
all these strange pockmarks

00:51:50.880 --> 00:51:53.980 align:middle line:90%
and circular grooves in it.

00:51:53.980 --> 00:51:58.320 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, archeologists
have wondered

00:51:58.320 --> 00:52:03.190 align:middle line:84%
about these strange
pockmarks on this head

00:52:03.190 --> 00:52:09.200 align:middle line:84%
because it's like after it had
been carved as a complete stone

00:52:09.200 --> 00:52:15.360 align:middle line:84%
head, someone then took
what was a power tool

00:52:15.360 --> 00:52:20.360 align:middle line:84%
and was basically
dishing out parts

00:52:20.360 --> 00:52:26.400 align:middle line:84%
of the head with this power
tool in an effort to deface it.

00:52:26.400 --> 00:52:28.320 align:middle line:84%
And this has baffled
archeologists

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:29.780 align:middle line:90%
for a number of reasons.

00:52:29.780 --> 00:52:32.740 align:middle line:84%
One, they don't know
why someone would

00:52:32.740 --> 00:52:37.360 align:middle line:84%
try to deface this basalt
head with these pockmarks.

00:52:37.360 --> 00:52:40.040 align:middle line:84%
And they can't figure
out how these marks would

00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:45.100 align:middle line:84%
have been made on the head
because, in their mind,

00:52:45.100 --> 00:52:47.210 align:middle line:84%
the Olmecs were
primitive people.

00:52:47.210 --> 00:52:49.590 align:middle line:84%
They didn't have
knowledge of the wheel.

00:52:49.590 --> 00:52:51.970 align:middle line:84%
Of course, they didn't
have power tools.

00:52:51.970 --> 00:52:55.810 align:middle line:84%
But how they could have bashed
out these little circular

00:52:55.810 --> 00:52:58.870 align:middle line:84%
pockmarks, they
can't figure out.

00:52:58.870 --> 00:53:02.560 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, they have
all of the indications

00:53:02.560 --> 00:53:05.880 align:middle line:84%
of being some kind
of a power tool

00:53:05.880 --> 00:53:09.190 align:middle line:84%
that was dishing out these
little circular holes

00:53:09.190 --> 00:53:11.250 align:middle line:90%
on this basalt head.

00:53:11.250 --> 00:53:16.150 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:53:16.150 --> 00:53:25.970 align:middle line:90%


00:53:25.970 --> 00:53:30.380 align:middle line:84%
The Olmecs were also known
for cranial deformation.

00:53:30.380 --> 00:53:34.220 align:middle line:84%
They were, as I
sometimes call them,

00:53:34.220 --> 00:53:40.640 align:middle line:84%
cone heads, like in South
America and other areas

00:53:40.640 --> 00:53:45.950 align:middle line:84%
of the world like Malta, the
Kurds, the [INAUDIBLE] in Egypt

00:53:45.950 --> 00:53:50.600 align:middle line:84%
like Akhenaten and Nefertiti,
and their children all

00:53:50.600 --> 00:53:54.580 align:middle line:90%
also had elongated craniums.

00:53:54.580 --> 00:53:57.520 align:middle line:84%
This was done also,
apparently, in ancient China.

00:53:57.520 --> 00:53:59.980 align:middle line:84%
It was done on remote
Pacific Islands like Vanuatu.

00:53:59.980 --> 00:54:02.760 align:middle line:90%


00:54:02.760 --> 00:54:06.920 align:middle line:84%
And the Olmecs are
particularly well known

00:54:06.920 --> 00:54:13.050 align:middle line:84%
for having these
deformed cranium.

00:54:13.050 --> 00:54:15.480 align:middle line:84%
What the purpose of
that was we don't know.

00:54:15.480 --> 00:54:21.940 align:middle line:84%
Some of these people had
crania that was twice

00:54:21.940 --> 00:54:26.900 align:middle line:90%
the size of our own heads.

00:54:26.900 --> 00:54:28.600 align:middle line:90%
How were they doing this?

00:54:28.600 --> 00:54:30.780 align:middle line:84%
One of the ways that,
apparently, they

00:54:30.780 --> 00:54:35.910 align:middle line:84%
did it was they
took a baby's head

00:54:35.910 --> 00:54:43.010 align:middle line:84%
and the plates in your
head haven't fused yet

00:54:43.010 --> 00:54:44.640 align:middle line:90%
when you're a small baby.

00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:50.600 align:middle line:84%
And by binding the head, you're
able to elongate the skull

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:53.090 align:middle line:90%
and essentially deform it.

00:54:53.090 --> 00:54:59.730 align:middle line:84%
Some of these people had their
heads flattened and very wide.

00:54:59.730 --> 00:55:04.220 align:middle line:84%
Others had their heads
extremely elongated

00:55:04.220 --> 00:55:09.440 align:middle line:84%
so that they were narrow and
came to a top, as a conehead.

00:55:09.440 --> 00:55:12.910 align:middle line:84%
We don't know why
people did this.

00:55:12.910 --> 00:55:16.300 align:middle line:84%
But it was a practice
used throughout the world

00:55:16.300 --> 00:55:18.940 align:middle line:90%
and is quite unusual.

00:55:18.940 --> 00:55:25.300 align:middle line:84%
Just cranial deformation
in itself is, in some way,

00:55:25.300 --> 00:55:30.946 align:middle line:84%
evidence for ocean going
travel, trans-Pacific,

00:55:30.946 --> 00:55:35.230 align:middle line:84%
trans-Atlantic
kind of voyager's.

00:55:35.230 --> 00:55:41.430 align:middle line:84%
The idea that people in Africa,
and the Middle East, and China,

00:55:41.430 --> 00:55:43.700 align:middle line:84%
and remote Pacific
islands, and in Mexico,

00:55:43.700 --> 00:55:47.540 align:middle line:84%
and South America, even
the Chinook Indians

00:55:47.540 --> 00:55:54.330 align:middle line:84%
all did this separately
and invented it separately,

00:55:54.330 --> 00:55:57.530 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't seem right.

00:55:57.530 --> 00:56:02.280 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is something that
people had to learn culturally.

00:56:02.280 --> 00:56:07.940 align:middle line:84%
And it is, to say the
least, highly unusual.

00:56:07.940 --> 00:56:11.630 align:middle line:84%
Notice here, on
this Olmec statue,

00:56:11.630 --> 00:56:15.740 align:middle line:84%
he's wearing a top knot on
his head, which may have

00:56:15.740 --> 00:56:18.550 align:middle line:90%
been the way he wore his hair.

00:56:18.550 --> 00:56:22.760 align:middle line:84%
We find this curious
topknot on the head

00:56:22.760 --> 00:56:27.580 align:middle line:84%
is also found in the
statues of Easter Island.

00:56:27.580 --> 00:56:33.410 align:middle line:84%
One of the really strange
statues in the museum

00:56:33.410 --> 00:56:36.670 align:middle line:84%
is the statue that
looks very Egyptian.

00:56:36.670 --> 00:56:39.530 align:middle line:84%
Notice that he is
apparently wearing the false

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:42.830 align:middle line:84%
beard that we associate
so much with the pharaohs.

00:56:42.830 --> 00:56:46.470 align:middle line:90%


00:56:46.470 --> 00:56:48.740 align:middle line:84%
Other parts of his
head, too, seem

00:56:48.740 --> 00:56:53.750 align:middle line:84%
to be Egyptian-type pharaonic
headdress that he's wearing.

00:56:53.750 --> 00:57:00.630 align:middle line:90%


00:57:00.630 --> 00:57:02.860 align:middle line:84%
Looking at this
sculpture, you might

00:57:02.860 --> 00:57:06.320 align:middle line:84%
think you were in a
museum in Cairo, Egypt.

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:10.700 align:middle line:84%
Notice here again how his
hands are on his knees.

00:57:10.700 --> 00:57:13.940 align:middle line:84%
This is known as the
[INAUDIBLE] position.

00:57:13.940 --> 00:57:16.110 align:middle line:84%
He's wearing an
unusual headdress

00:57:16.110 --> 00:57:18.740 align:middle line:90%
with the ball in front.

00:57:18.740 --> 00:57:21.260 align:middle line:84%
It's possible that there
was a snake here too.

00:57:21.260 --> 00:57:23.910 align:middle line:84%
This altar would have
been very Egyptian.

00:57:23.910 --> 00:57:28.330 align:middle line:84%
His headdress as well
is very Egyptian.

00:57:28.330 --> 00:57:33.120 align:middle line:84%
It's a very fine and
well made statue.

00:57:33.120 --> 00:57:37.530 align:middle line:84%
Some Olmec statues are
extremely unusual, even

00:57:37.530 --> 00:57:41.210 align:middle line:84%
abstract in their nature,
something you might

00:57:41.210 --> 00:57:45.350 align:middle line:90%
find in a modern art museum.

00:57:45.350 --> 00:57:47.340 align:middle line:84%
One of the interesting
things about the Olmecs

00:57:47.340 --> 00:57:52.050 align:middle line:84%
too is that their
core area is known

00:57:52.050 --> 00:57:54.600 align:middle line:90%
as the Isthmus of Tehuantepec.

00:57:54.600 --> 00:57:59.070 align:middle line:10%
And the isthmus of Tehuantepec
is that narrow part

00:57:59.070 --> 00:58:03.220 align:middle line:10%
of Mexico in the very south.

00:58:03.220 --> 00:58:07.810 align:middle line:84%
And it's where Mexico
is at its narrowest,

00:58:07.810 --> 00:58:12.450 align:middle line:84%
between the Atlantic Ocean
and the Pacific Ocean.

00:58:12.450 --> 00:58:16.460 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, this is the
core area of the Olmecs.

00:58:16.460 --> 00:58:21.390 align:middle line:84%
And the Olmecs were
really on both coasts.

00:58:21.390 --> 00:58:25.840 align:middle line:84%
They were on the Atlantic
Coast and on the Pacific coast.

00:58:25.840 --> 00:58:33.310 align:middle line:84%
So the Olmecs could have had
ultimately ports on two oceans.

00:58:33.310 --> 00:58:35.700 align:middle line:84%
This Isthmus of
Tehuantepec too has

00:58:35.700 --> 00:58:41.810 align:middle line:84%
a lot in common with today's
current Panama Canal.

00:58:41.810 --> 00:58:46.230 align:middle line:84%
Back in the 1800s, when
the Panama Canal was first

00:58:46.230 --> 00:58:48.940 align:middle line:84%
being conceived,
there were three areas

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:52.230 align:middle line:84%
in Central America that
were being considered

00:58:52.230 --> 00:58:59.030 align:middle line:84%
to try and create a transit
zone between the Atlantic

00:58:59.030 --> 00:59:00.710 align:middle line:90%
and the Pacific.

00:59:00.710 --> 00:59:03.270 align:middle line:84%
Panama was, of course,
being considered

00:59:03.270 --> 00:59:06.410 align:middle line:84%
because it had a series of
lakes and was a narrow area.

00:59:06.410 --> 00:59:10.480 align:middle line:84%
Nicaragua was also being
considered for this

00:59:10.480 --> 00:59:15.450 align:middle line:84%
because boats could
come from the Atlantic

00:59:15.450 --> 00:59:19.420 align:middle line:84%
into Lake Nicaragua and they
could get very, very close

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:20.470 align:middle line:90%
to the Pacific Ocean.

00:59:20.470 --> 00:59:24.840 align:middle line:84%
However, there was still a
narrow but high mountain range

00:59:24.840 --> 00:59:28.370 align:middle line:84%
that's separating Lake
Nicaragua with the Pacific.

00:59:28.370 --> 00:59:30.640 align:middle line:84%
The third area
that was considered

00:59:30.640 --> 00:59:34.470 align:middle line:84%
was the isthmus of
Tehuantepec in Mexico.

00:59:34.470 --> 00:59:37.920 align:middle line:84%
And what the Mexican
government ultimately did

00:59:37.920 --> 00:59:44.390 align:middle line:84%
was build a railroad between
the Atlantic and the Pacific

00:59:44.390 --> 00:59:47.080 align:middle line:90%
to bridge this narrow area.

00:59:47.080 --> 00:59:50.120 align:middle line:84%
But it's kind of curious
because the Olmecs themselves

00:59:50.120 --> 00:59:57.515 align:middle line:84%
had already realized that,
yeah, this area was--

00:59:57.515 --> 01:00:01.280 align:middle line:84%
the Tehuantepec
isthmus in Mexico

01:00:01.280 --> 01:00:08.370 align:middle line:84%
was an area where you could
have ports on the Pacific

01:00:08.370 --> 01:00:10.010 align:middle line:90%
and ports on the Atlantic.

01:00:10.010 --> 01:00:12.310 align:middle line:84%
And right in the
middle of that area

01:00:12.310 --> 01:00:16.920 align:middle line:84%
was the early megalithic
cities in Mexico,

01:00:16.920 --> 01:00:20.420 align:middle line:90%
such as Monte Alban and Mitla.

01:00:20.420 --> 01:00:24.250 align:middle line:84%
And these areas too were part
of the heartland of the Olmecs

01:00:24.250 --> 01:00:29.940 align:middle line:84%
and ultimately became
Mixtec and Zapotec cities.

01:00:29.940 --> 01:00:33.950 align:middle line:84%
Here's another example of
the very unusual Olmec art

01:00:33.950 --> 01:00:35.970 align:middle line:90%
and style.

01:00:35.970 --> 01:00:38.040 align:middle line:90%
It's very distinct.

01:00:38.040 --> 01:00:42.340 align:middle line:84%
But the stylization is so
unique, almost futuristic.

01:00:42.340 --> 01:00:46.140 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

01:00:46.140 --> 01:00:51.370 align:middle line:90%


01:00:51.370 --> 01:00:53.870 align:middle line:84%
It's thought that the
Olmecs were the mother

01:00:53.870 --> 01:00:56.170 align:middle line:90%
culture of Mesoamerica.

01:00:56.170 --> 01:01:00.560 align:middle line:84%
As archeologists
studied the Olmecs,

01:01:00.560 --> 01:01:07.220 align:middle line:84%
they realized that many of the
things that had been previously

01:01:07.220 --> 01:01:10.930 align:middle line:84%
ascribed to the
Mayans having invented

01:01:10.930 --> 01:01:14.240 align:middle line:84%
had really been invented
by the Olmecs before them.

01:01:14.240 --> 01:01:18.950 align:middle line:84%
And we're talking about the
Mayan calendar, the number

01:01:18.950 --> 01:01:24.750 align:middle line:84%
system, the hieroglyphic
system, even the building

01:01:24.750 --> 01:01:28.650 align:middle line:84%
of early Mayan pyramids such
as the ones at Uaxactun,

01:01:28.650 --> 01:01:30.410 align:middle line:90%
north of Tikal.

01:01:30.410 --> 01:01:34.810 align:middle line:84%
All of these things really
began with the Olmecs.

01:01:34.810 --> 01:01:38.570 align:middle line:84%
And it was the Mayans
who essentially inherited

01:01:38.570 --> 01:01:44.210 align:middle line:84%
all of this scientific
knowledge that ultimately

01:01:44.210 --> 01:01:46.490 align:middle line:90%
came from the Olmecs.

01:01:46.490 --> 01:01:49.710 align:middle line:84%
Year after year, archeologists
discover new things

01:01:49.710 --> 01:01:53.760 align:middle line:84%
about the Olmecs, pushing
them farther back in time

01:01:53.760 --> 01:01:57.250 align:middle line:84%
and deeper into the
heart of Mexico.

01:01:57.250 --> 01:02:01.100 align:middle line:84%
Only recently archeologists have
discovered the oldest writing

01:02:01.100 --> 01:02:04.330 align:middle line:90%
in the Americas, which is Olmec.

01:02:04.330 --> 01:02:10.540 align:middle line:84%
Also they've discovered Olmec
remains near Mexico City.

01:02:10.540 --> 01:02:15.680 align:middle line:84%
What caused the collapse of
this great early civilization?

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:18.592 align:middle line:84%
We may never know the
secrets of the Olmecs.

01:02:18.592 --> 01:02:22.980 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

01:02:22.980 --> 01:02:48.810 align:middle line:90%


01:02:48.810 --> 01:02:53.880 align:middle line:84%
Next we'll be continuing
our adventures in Mexico,

01:02:53.880 --> 01:02:58.400 align:middle line:84%
going to the Great Pyramid
of Cholula in central Mexico

01:02:58.400 --> 01:03:03.420 align:middle line:84%
and to the enigmatic pyramids
of Teotihuacan and Tula.

01:03:03.420 --> 01:03:09.220 align:middle line:84%
And then north over the border
into Arizona and New Mexico

01:03:09.220 --> 01:03:11.960 align:middle line:84%
to look for the lost cities
and ancient mysteries

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:12.760 align:middle line:90%
of the southwest.

01:03:12.760 --> 01:03:14.310 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

01:03:14.310 --> 01:03:33.744 align:middle line:90%